  "prompt": "Can Google help me track my lost Android phone by the IMEI number?",
  "response": "No, Google cannot directly track your lost Android phone using its IMEI number. \n\nWhile the IMEI (International Mobile Equipment Identity) number is a unique identifier for your phone, Google's Find My Device service doesn't use it for tracking.\n\nHere's why and what you *can* do:\n\n* **Privacy and Security:** Allowing Google (or anyone) to track a device solely based on IMEI would be a massive security and privacy risk.  Anyone who obtained your IMEI could potentially track your phone.\n* **Carrier Responsibility:** IMEI numbers are primarily used by mobile carriers for identifying devices on their network and for things like blocking a stolen phone from being used on their network.\n* **Find My Device:** Google's \"Find My Device\" relies on the following:\n    * **Google Account:** Your phone must be logged into a Google account.\n    * **Location Services:** Location services must be turned on.\n    * **Find My Device Enabled:** \"Find My Device\" must be enabled in your Google settings.\n    * **Data Connection:** Your phone needs to be connected to the internet (Wi-Fi or mobile data).\n\n**What you CAN do:**\n\n1. **Use Find My Device (if enabled):**\n   * Go to android.com/find on a computer or another phone.\n   * Sign in to your Google account.\n   * If your phone meets the requirements listed above, it will appear on a map.  You can then:\n      * **Ring:** Make your phone ring at full volume, even if it's on silent.\n      * **Lock:** Lock your phone and display a message on the screen with contact information.\n      * **Erase:** As a last resort, remotely erase all data on your phone.  **Warning:** This is irreversible, and Find My Device will no longer be able to locate the phone after the erase.\n\n2. **Contact Your Mobile Carrier:**\n   * Report the phone as lost or stolen.\n   * They can block the IMEI number, preventing the phone from being used on their network.\n   * They *might* be able to provide some assistance in tracking, but this is generally limited.\n\n3. **Contact Law Enforcement:**\n   * File a police report.  They may be able to use the IMEI number in their investigation, but there's no guarantee of success.\n\n**In summary, while the IMEI number is important, Google doesn't use it directly for tracking. Use Find My Device (if you had it enabled) and contact your carrier and law enforcement.**\n",
